  california:
    "California is where the modern American food-truck scene was invented. Roy Choi's Kogi BBQ in Los Angeles fused Korean and Mexican on a single tortilla in 2008 and the format hasn't looked back. The state spans every register — taco trucks in East LA that have been there for generations, ferment-and-foam fine-dining experiments in Oakland, fish-taco operations up and down the coast, and a Bay Area scene shaped by tech-worker lunches and pop-up culture. Permissive city regulations (especially in LA) and a year-round outdoor eating climate make California the country's deepest bench, by a wide margin.",

  texas:
    "Texas is the BBQ capital of the truck world and one of the country's most prolific Tex-Mex incubators. Austin's Central Texas-style brisket scene — post-oak smoke, salt-and-pepper rub, sliced to order on butcher paper — sets the bar for slow-smoked beef. Houston brings East Texas saucier ribs and a fierce Vietnamese bánh mì scene. San Antonio anchors South Texas barbacoa and breakfast-taco country. Dallas hosts a younger truck culture that mixes them all. Across the state, you'll find trucks that have run from the same lot for decades alongside week-one operators chasing the next great brisket. For a deeper breakdown, read our Texas BBQ guide.",

  'new-york':
    "New York's food truck scene is shaped by Manhattan's relentless lunch rush and the city's unmatched immigrant density. The halal cart — chicken or lamb over rice with white sauce — is a New York invention that has gone national. Taco trucks have taken over the Lower East Side and Chelsea, Indian kati-roll carts feed Midtown's office workers, and Brooklyn's Smorgasburg festival circuit has launched a generation of operators into national prominence. The space is brutal — permit caps, parking enforcement, weather — but the trucks that survive any of it tend to be very, very good. Read our local NYC guide for specific picks.",

  florida:
    "Florida's food truck scene is, like the state itself, three or four scenes pretending to be one. Miami is Cuban-and-Caribbean-forward — pressed sandwiches, ropa vieja bowls, mariquitas. Orlando's truck culture grew up around theme-park workers and runs late into the night. Tampa has a serious Cuban tradition rooted in Ybor City. Jacksonville and the Panhandle lean Southern and seafood-heavy. The whole state benefits from year-round outdoor eating weather and a constant influx of new operators trying their first menu on customers who can be charitable. Bring an appetite for fried things and a tolerance for humidity.",

  oregon:
    "Portland built the model of the food-truck pod — clusters of permanent trucks parked on a single lot, sharing seating and bathrooms, open year-round in defiance of the weather. The format works because Portland's regulations practically invited it and because the city's population takes food experiments seriously. You'll find Thai noodle operations that have been parked in the same spot for fifteen years next to week-old operators trying out fusion concepts. The trucks have collectively shaped Portland's reputation as one of the country's most adventurous food cities. The pods are concentrated downtown, in Northeast, and along Southeast Hawthorne.",

  tennessee:
    "Tennessee's food-truck scene is anchored by Nashville's white-hot hot-chicken trucks and Memphis's barbecue tradition — both regional dishes that have gone national in the last decade. Nashville's truck culture exploded as the city did, with operators experimenting alongside the hot-chicken explosion to figure out where the form ends. Memphis stays closer to the smokehouse tradition: dry-rubbed ribs, pulled pork shoulders, sticky pit-tomato sauce on the side. Knoxville and Chattanooga add scrappier scenes that pull from both poles. The whole state benefits from a long warm season and a permissive regulatory environment.",

  'new-jersey':
    "New Jersey's food truck scene runs on commuter density and an outsized Italian-American restaurant tradition. The Newark and Jersey City scenes are aggressive Portuguese, Brazilian, and Cuban — bringing a flavor of the diaspora to street level. The Princeton and Hoboken trucks lean upscale, often staffed by chefs who trained at New York restaurants and decamped across the river. South Jersey has a serious sub-and-cheesesteak culture that holds its own against Philly. New Jersey trucks tend to be unpretentious, generously portioned, and slightly less Instagram-friendly than their Manhattan counterparts. That's a feature, not a bug.",

  pennsylvania:
    "Pennsylvania's food trucks are mostly a Philadelphia and Pittsburgh story. Philly's cheesesteak truck tradition runs deep, but the more interesting action is in the city's halal carts, taco trucks, and Vietnamese bánh mì operators that feed the office workers around City Hall and the Penn campus. Pittsburgh's scene is younger and rougher around the edges — pierogi trucks, Polish-American comfort food, a serious BBQ contingent in the Strip District. State permitting is fragmented by city, which means each scene developed differently. The trucks tend to be solidly old-school in the best sense.",

  illinois:
    "Chicago's food truck scene exists in spite of itself. For years the city ran a 200-foot proximity rule that effectively banned trucks from operating near restaurants, which is most of the city. Recent reforms have loosened that, and the result is a scene that's young, hungry, and fiercely independent. Polish and Mexican operators dominate the established ranks; a new generation is bringing Korean, Filipino, and Ethiopian onto the street. Outside Chicago, the scene thins out fast — Springfield and the college towns have a few operators each, and that's roughly it.",

  georgia:
    "Atlanta's food truck scene punches well above the state's overall weight class. The city's Asian-American and African-American food cultures both show up on wheels in serious ways — Korean-fried-chicken trucks, soul-food trucks doing things that the brick-and-mortar restaurants don't dare, vegetarian operations running on a Sunday-supper cadence. Savannah's smaller scene leans coastal Southern (shrimp and grits, low-country boil), and Athens supports a college-driven truck culture that has produced a few breakout operators. State regulations are permissive enough to let operators experiment.",
